Assortative mating and sibling GWAS

Gibran Hemani

Model

Parent 1

\[ \textbf{y}_1 = \textbf{1}\mu + \textbf{G}_1\textbf{b} + \textbf{c}_1 + \textbf{e}_1 \]

The child’s value of \(c\) is

\[ \textbf{c}_o = (\textbf{c}_1 + \textbf{c}_2) / \sqrt{2} \]

Heritability is estimated as:

\[ h^2 = \frac{\sigma_a^2}{\sigma_a^2 + \sigma_c^2 + \sigma_e^2} \]

where

\[ \sigma_a^2 = \sum^M 2pq\beta^2 \]

Under assortative mating the SNP variance increases and the common environment variance increases, so the overall phenotypic variance increases. The SNP effect estimate in a within family model will be adjusted correctly but the common environment will not, so the ratio will be distorted

Sibling estimates of SNP effects are unbiased

res %>% 
  tidyr::gather(key = "method", value = "bias", pop, sib_dod, sib_fe, pop_fe, trio, -c(sib_vargbv:h2_true)) %>%
  filter(method != "pop_fe") %>%
  ggplot(., aes(x=spouse_cor, y=bias)) +
  geom_point(aes(colour=method)) +
  geom_smooth(method="lm", aes(colour=method)) +
  facet_grid(vg ~ vc) +
  scale_colour_brewer(type="qual")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Sibling estimates of heritability are biased

res %>% 
  dplyr::select(-c(pop:vg_sib, vg_pop, vg_true)) %>%
  tidyr::gather(key = "method", value = "bias", h2_sib, h2_pop, h2_true) %>%
  ggplot(., aes(x=spouse_cor, y=bias)) +
  geom_point(aes(colour=method)) +
  geom_smooth(method="lm", aes(colour=method)) +
